passages.text: F3Q25 Recap: Topline Strength as Instrument Demand Shows Signs of Continued Improvement, Offset by Margin Pressure Dutof Tariffs; Reiterate OW

After the close, Agilent (A) reported a F3Q25 top- line beat alongside in- line adj. EPS, while raising 2025 top- line guidance and reiterating the adj. EPS midpoint. The company reported F3Q25 revenues of \(1.74B\) (vs. Street of \(1.67B\) and guide of \(1.65 - 1.68B\) ) or core growth of \(+6.1\%\) (vs. Street of \(+2.9\%\) and guide of \(+1.7 - 3.6\%\) ) while adj. OPM of \(25.1\%\) (vs. Street of \(26.6\%\) ) translated to adj. EPS of \(1.37\) (vs. Street of \(1.37\) and guide of \(1.35 - 1.37\) ). Strength in the quarter was broad- based led by LDG \(+7\%\) core y/y (vs. guide of \(+\) MSD) including \(+\) LDD growth in LC and LCMS (B2B \(>1.0\) ) as the replacement cycle continues to improve, alongside high- \(20\%\) core y/y growth in NASD. Additionally, AMG and ACG both grew \(5\%\) core y/y (vs. guidance of \(+\) LSD for both, respectively). From an end- market perspective, Pharma & Biotech grew \(+9\%\) core y/y with management noting that customers are seeing better access to budgets and "...a reduced dependence on executive level approvals that have slowed or stopped spending in the recent past". Additionally, A&G returned to growth \((+1\%\) core y/y) despite continued softness in the U.S., and Chemical & Energy grew \(+10\%\) core y/y driven by increased capital investment in semis and chemicals. On the bottom- line, adj. OPM in the quarter of \(25.1\%\) (vs. Street of \(26.6\%\) ) missed Agilent's internal expectations by \(\sim 140\) bps per management in our follow up, driven equally by 3 factors: 1) higher revenue/volume driving increased net tariff costs (tariffs were a \(- 200\) bps y/y headwind to margins in the quarter as tariffs were a \(\) 35M\(headwind vs. expectations of\) \ \(25M\) ); 2) increased variable pay expectations driven by stronger overall performance; and 3) commercial investment ahead of expected increased demand. Looking ahead, the company raised FY25 guidance now calling for revenues of \(\) 6.91- 6.93B\( (vs. Street of\) \ \(6.79B\) and prior guide of \(\) 6.73- 6.81B\(), or core growth of \(+4.3 - 4.6\%\) (vs. Street of \(+3.3\%\) and prior guide of \(+2.5 - 3.5\%\) ) while the adj. EPS range now calls for \(\) 5.56- 5.59\(, with the prior midpoint reiterated (vs. Street of\) \ \(5.58\) and prior guide of \(\) 5.54- 5.61\(). The guide translates to F4Q company revenues of\) \ \(1.822 - 1.842B\) (vs. Street of \(\) 1.78B\() or \(+4.8 - 6.0\%\) core growth (vs. Street of \(+3.6\%\) ) alongside adj. EPS of \(\) 1.57- 1.60\( (vs. Street of\) \ \(1.60\) ). On the tap- line in F4Q25, Agilent assumes Pharma & Biotech will grow \(+\) MSD/HSD \(\) \text{arr} \(the back of stable to improving conditions as customer budgets for the instrument replacement cycle continue to grow, with early indications of a more standard year- end budget flush. On the bottom- line, the F4Q25 guide assumes a\) \sim +230\(bps q/q step up in adj. OPM (translating to}\) \sim 27.4\% \(vs. Street of\) 28.7\% \() with most of the improvement coming from leveraging fixed costs driven by the q/q increase in volume. On the tariff piece, the FY25 guide now assumes a\) \ \(20M\) net impact vs. prior assumption of minimal net impact, though management reiterated that it expects to fully mitigate tariffs in 2026 at current rates. Stepping back, while Agilent experienced some tariff- related noise in the quarter as we detail below, the company encouragingly reiterated expectations to fully mitigate the impacts in FY26. However, on our follow up management clarified that part of its tariff mitigation efforts involve margin neutral pricing measures and advised investors to not overstate the potential margin tariff tailwind to margins. In terms of other FY26 nuggets, on our follow up management indicated that it would expect NASD to grow +DD next year given the recent approval momentum in the space, although noted that the step up in costs associated with expected capacity coming on line will limit the margin impact from the step up in revenue. Additionally, as it relates to China stimulus, management noted to us in our follow up that while no stimulus benefit is factored into F4Q guidance, Agilent expects stimulus orders in F4Q and sized the opportunity at \(\sim\) \(\)130-150M\(for FY26.\)

- F3Q25 top-line in detail. Agilent reported F3Q25 revenues of \(\) 1.74B\(above the Street of\) \ \(1.67B\) and above guide of \(\) 1.65-1.68B\(, with core growth of\)+6.1\%\(y/y (above both the Street of\)+2.9\%\(core and guide of\)1.7-3.6\%\(, while M&A contributed +1.9\%\) and FX contributed +2.1\% translating to +10.1\% reported growth. Notably, Agilent saw +100bps improvement in pricing (vs. +50bps last year) which did not include surcharges in the quarter (expected in F4Q25 and FY26). Diving deeper, LDG grew +7\% core y/y (+14\% reported vs. guide of +MSD) to \(\) 670M\(driven by +LDD growth in LC and LCMS instruments including Infinity III growth of +mid-teens. Agilent called out B2B >1.0 in its instrument business in the quarter. Additionally, Agilent also called out CDMO core growth of +high-20\% range which consisted solely of NASD in the quarter given Biovectra is still inorganic. That said, management noted to us in our follow up that Biovectra grew y/y despite headwinds related to the previously communicated plant facility shutdown related to a large customer transition to a higher throughput process. AMG grew +5\% core y/y (+7\% reported vs. guide of +LSD) and grew to \(\) 324M\(as GC, GCMS and Spectroscopy all saw nice momentum across end-markets; and ACG increased +5\% core y/y (+8\% reported vs. prior guide of +LSD) to\) \ \(744M\) driven by solid lab activity as Agilent's service business grew +MSD led by strength in applied markets in Europe and consumables grew +MSD with no indication of pull forward. By end market, Pharma & Biotech (36\% of F3Q revenue) grew +9\% core y/y driven by +LDD growth in small-molecule tied to demand for downstream QA/QC along with an increasing replacement cycle, while biopharma grew +HSD overall, and Agilent was upbeat on NASD revenue growth in the quarter noting that orders seen in F3Q support an increasing confidence in reaching +DD growth for FY25 (vs. prior NASD expectations of +HSD nudging +DD growth); Chem & Advanced Materials (23\% of F3Q revenue) grew +10\% core y/y driven by a demand rebound across geographies led by new investments in semiconductor fab facilities as well as robust demand in the chemical sector. Dx & Clinical (15\% of F3Q revenue) grew +4\% core y/y driven by +HSD growth in Dakota cinder dx ex-China (though Agilent noted little China VBP impact); A&G (8\% of F3Q revenue) grew +1\% core y/y despite continued funding pressure in the U.S.; Food (9\% of F3Q revenue) grew +7\% core y/y driven by mid-20\% growth in Asia driven by increasing safety regulations; and E&F (9\% of F3Q revenue) declined -5\% core y/y driven by changes at the U.S. EPA driving customer caution in new capital spending. That said, PFAS grew +LDD y/y vs. tough comps last year of \(\sim +50\%\) (vs. \(> + 70\%\) y/y in F2Q25) with strong OUS growth of low-30\% offsetting -20\% declines in Americas driven by the changes to the U.S. EPA, which has not impacted testing volumes (Americas PFAS related consumables and services grew +HSD) but has driven incremental uncertainty on capex spend in the near term which management expects will be a transitory dynamic. Lastly by region, the Americas grew +5\% core y/y; APAC ex-China grew +10\% core y/y with China growing +4\% core y/y; India grew +20\% core y/y; and Europe grew +7\% core y/y. In terms of China stimulus, management indicated that it saw some government funding flow into A&G customers in the quarter and that based on the company's interactions with local officials, would expect a more meaningful stimulus contribution toward the end of the calendar year, particularly in applied markets in the region.

- F3Q25 margins and bottom-line detail. Moving down the P&L, adj. GM declined - 300bps y/y to 53.1% (vs. Street of 54.7%) and OPM was -230bps y/y to 25.1% (vs. Street of 26.6%), leading to adj. EPS of \(1.37 (in-line with the Street\) 1.37 and guide of \(1.35 - 1.37\) . On the margin side, management noted to us on our follow up that adj. OPM missed Agilent's internal expectations by \(\sim 140\) bps driven equally by 3 factors: 1) higher revenue/ volume driving increased net tariff costs (tariffs were a -200bps y/y headwind to margins in the quarter); 2) increased variable pay expectations driven by stronger overall performance; and 3) commercial investment ahead of expected increased demand. It is worth noting that margins also saw y/y headwinds related to currency and the Biovectra site shutdown. From a tariff cost perspective, Agilent had previously assumed a \(\) 25M\(impact in F3Q25, which turned out to be\) \ \(35M\) in the quarter.

- For more on A: See our NIH Budget note, CFO transition note, ASMS Conference note, PFAS lab takeaways, thoughts post Tariff announcements, Agilent F2Q25 note, Agilent AD recap note, and Biovectra acquisition note.
